export const questionBank19 = [
  {q:"A company uses Amazon S3 and needs to replicate objects from a source bucket to a destination bucket in ANOTHER AWS account. The destination account should OWN the replicated objects (not the source account). How is this configured?", opts:["S3 Cross-Region Replication with default settings (source account retains ownership)","S3 Replication with 'Change object ownership to destination bucket owner' option enabled in the replication rule. The destination bucket must have a policy allowing the source account to replicate and set the ACL.","Object ownership can't be changed during replication","Use AWS DataSync instead of S3 replication for cross-account"], correct:1, exp:"S3 Replication supports ownership override: enable 'Change object ownership to destination bucket owner' in the replication configuration. Without this, replicated objects are owned by the source account (destination account can't manage them). With ownership override: the destination account owns and fully controls replicated objects. Prerequisites: destination bucket policy grants source account s3:ReplicateObject + s3:ObjectOwnerOverrideToBucketOwner permissions.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company runs a financial application that requires the database to survive the complete failure of an AWS Region. They need RPO < 1 second and RTO < 1 minute. Which database deployment?", opts:["RDS Multi-AZ (single region only — doesn't survive region failure)","Aurora Global Database with write forwarding (RPO ~1 second with asynchronous replication, RTO ~1 minute with managed failover to secondary region)","DynamoDB Global Tables (eventually consistent cross-region, RPO could be several seconds)","RDS Cross-Region Read Replicas (manual promotion, RTO > 1 minute)"], correct:1, exp:"Aurora Global Database: primary region handles writes, secondary regions (up to 5) replicate asynchronously with typical lag <1 second (meets RPO <1 second). Managed planned failover or unplanned failover promotes a secondary to primary in ~1 minute. Write forwarding allows secondary regions to forward writes to primary. DynamoDB Global Tables has eventual consistency (RPO could be higher). RDS cross-region replicas require manual promotion (slower RTO).", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store to manage configuration. They store a database connection string as a SecureString parameter (encrypted with KMS). A Lambda function needs to read this parameter. What permissions are required?", opts:["Only ssm:GetParameter permission","BOTH ssm:GetParameter on the parameter AND kms:Decrypt on the KMS key used to encrypt the SecureString. Without KMS permission, the API call succeeds but the value can't be decrypted.","Only kms:Decrypt permission","Lambda has automatic access to all SSM parameters"], correct:1, exp:"SecureString parameters are encrypted with a KMS key. To read the decrypted value, the Lambda role needs: (1) ssm:GetParameter (or ssm:GetParameters) on the parameter ARN, (2) kms:Decrypt on the KMS key ARN. If you request WithDecryption=true (default for SecureString), both permissions are evaluated. If only SSM permission exists without KMS, the call either fails or returns encrypted ciphertext. This dual-permission model is consistent with all KMS-encrypted resources.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses CloudFront to deliver content globally. They want to serve different content based on the user's device type (mobile vs desktop). How can CloudFront determine the device type?", opts:["CloudFront can't determine device type","CloudFront adds device detection headers to the origin request: CloudFront-Is-Mobile-Viewer, CloudFront-Is-Desktop-Viewer, CloudFront-Is-Tablet-Viewer. Cache behavior must be configured to forward these headers (or use cache policy with included headers).","The origin must detect the device","Use Lambda@Edge to parse User-Agent manually"], correct:1, exp:"CloudFront parses the User-Agent header and adds simplified device-type headers: CloudFront-Is-Mobile-Viewer: true/false, CloudFront-Is-Desktop-Viewer: true/false, CloudFront-Is-Tablet-Viewer: true/false, CloudFront-Is-SmartTV-Viewer: true/false. Configure cache policy to include these headers (tells CloudFront to cache separate versions per device type). Origin uses these headers for content selection. No Lambda@Edge needed for basic device detection.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company needs to store 500TB of genomics data. The data is written once and read frequently for analysis. Reads are sequential (large scans of hundreds of GB). Cost is the priority, and they can tolerate slightly higher latency than standard S3. Which storage?", opts:["S3 Standard (too expensive for 500TB that's read-heavy)","S3 Intelligent-Tiering (monitoring costs on 500TB of frequently-accessed data)","S3 Standard-IA (cheaper storage but higher retrieval cost per GB — bad for frequent large reads)","S3 Express One Zone for frequently accessed data in a specific AZ (lowest latency but most expensive per GB)"], correct:0, exp:"For write-once, READ-FREQUENTLY data: S3 Standard is actually correct. S3 Standard-IA has a per-GB retrieval fee ($0.01/GB) — with 'read frequently' + 'hundreds of GB per read', retrieval costs would exceed the storage savings. At 500TB frequently read with large sequential scans, S3 Standard ($0.023/GB) without retrieval fees is most cost-effective. IA's cheaper storage rate is offset by the per-GB retrieval charge when reads are frequent.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Config Aggregator to view compliance data from multiple accounts. They notice one account is not reporting. What could be the issue?", opts:["Config Aggregator doesn't support multi-account","The source account must authorize the aggregator account (via Config authorization), OR if using Organizations, the aggregator must be in the management/delegated admin account with organization-level authorization","Config must be enabled in each source account separately (Config Aggregator doesn't enable Config — it only aggregates existing data)","Both B and C could be causes — the account needs Config enabled AND must authorize the aggregator"], correct:3, exp:"Two requirements for Config Aggregator to collect from a source account: (1) AWS Config must be ENABLED in the source account (Aggregator doesn't enable it — it only collects from accounts already running Config). (2) The source account must authorize the aggregator (via PutAggregationAuthorization) — OR use Organization-level aggregator (auto-authorized). Missing either: no data from that account. Common fix: enable Config in the source account and ensure authorization exists.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses CloudWatch Logs. Their application generates 1TB of logs daily. Most logs are for debugging and only needed if a problem occurs. They want to reduce CloudWatch Logs costs while keeping the ability to search recent logs. What approach?", opts:["Delete all logs immediately after ingestion","Send ALL logs to S3 (cheapest storage) via Kinesis Firehose, keep only ERROR/WARN in CloudWatch Logs for alerting and quick search. Use Athena to query S3 logs when detailed investigation is needed.","Reduce log retention to 1 day (still paying $0.50/GB ingestion for 1TB/day = $500/day)","Increase retention to reduce cost (retention doesn't affect ingestion cost)"], correct:1, exp:"Cost optimization strategy: (1) Filter at the source — only send ERROR/WARN/critical logs to CloudWatch Logs (reduces $0.50/GB ingestion cost dramatically). (2) Ship ALL logs (including DEBUG) to S3 via Kinesis Firehose ($0.01/GB = 50x cheaper than CloudWatch ingestion). (3) Query S3 logs with Athena on-demand when investigation is needed. Result: fast alerting on errors (CloudWatch), cheap storage of all logs (S3), searchable when needed (Athena). 90%+ cost reduction.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon ECS with Service Discovery (Cloud Map). Service A needs to call Service B by name (e.g., service-b.local). What does Cloud Map provide?", opts:["A load balancer between services","DNS-based service discovery — Cloud Map registers ECS tasks and creates DNS records (A records or SRV records) in a private DNS namespace. Service A resolves 'service-b.local' to the IP addresses of healthy Service B tasks.","A service mesh with mTLS","API Gateway between services"], correct:1, exp:"AWS Cloud Map (Service Discovery): ECS automatically registers/deregisters tasks as they start/stop. Creates DNS records in a Route 53 private hosted zone. Service A resolves service-b.local → gets IP addresses of healthy Service B tasks. Supports: DNS-based discovery (simple, no code changes) or API-based discovery (more metadata). Health checks automatically remove unhealthy instances from DNS. No load balancer needed for service-to-service communication — DNS provides the endpoints.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Lambda. They want to test a new version of their function with 10% of production traffic before fully rolling out. What Lambda feature enables this?", opts:["Lambda Versions + Aliases with weighted routing — create an alias pointing to both the current version (90%) and new version (10%). Traffic is split based on weights.","Deploy to a separate function and route via API Gateway","Use feature flags in application code","Lambda doesn't support gradual deployments"], correct:0, exp:"Lambda Aliases support traffic shifting (weighted routing) between two function versions. Create alias 'prod' pointing to: v1 (weight 90%) and v2 (weight 10%). 10% of invocations go to v2 (canary deployment). Monitor errors/latency. If good: shift to 100% v2. If bad: immediately shift to 100% v1 (instant rollback). This enables: canary deployments, blue/green (0/100 or 100/0), and linear rollouts. Integrates with CodeDeploy for automated rollout with alarms.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon Redshift. Data analysts complain that queries are slow after the warehouse has been idle for hours. The first query takes 2 minutes but subsequent queries on the same data take 5 seconds. What explains this?", opts:["Redshift instance is hibernating","Redshift uses a results cache — subsequent identical queries return cached results instantly. First query after idle requires loading data from disk into memory (S3-backed storage for RA3 nodes, or local SSD). This is expected 'cold cache' behavior.","Network latency to Redshift increases when idle","The JDBC connection timed out"], correct:1, exp:"Redshift performance depends on data being in memory (block cache). After idle periods, memory may be reclaimed. First query reads from disk (SSD or S3 for RA3 nodes) — slower. Subsequent queries on the same data read from memory cache — much faster. Additionally, Redshift Results Cache stores query results for identical queries (returned instantly without re-execution). Solutions: keep cluster warm with scheduled queries, or accept cold-start behavior. RA3 managed storage handles this automatically over time.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Transit Gateway (TGW) to connect 15 VPCs. They want to isolate groups: VPCs 1-5 (Production) should not communicate with VPCs 6-10 (Development), but both should access VPCs 11-15 (Shared Services). How?", opts:["Separate Transit Gateways per group (complex, expensive)","TGW Route Table isolation: create 3 route tables (Prod, Dev, Shared). Associate Prod VPCs with Prod table, Dev with Dev table, Shared with Shared table. Propagate: Shared routes to Prod and Dev tables. Prod/Dev don't propagate to each other's tables.","VPC Peering between groups (doesn't scale with 15 VPCs)","Security Groups to block cross-group traffic (SGs are per-instance, not per-VPC)"], correct:1, exp:"TGW route table segregation is the standard network isolation pattern: (1) Production route table: routes to Shared Services VPCs only (no Dev routes). (2) Development route table: routes to Shared Services only (no Prod routes). (3) Shared Services route table: routes to BOTH Prod and Dev (bidirectional access). Associate each VPC attachment with the appropriate route table. Result: Prod↔Shared ✓, Dev↔Shared ✓, Prod↔Dev ✗. Clean, scalable isolation.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses S3 event notifications to trigger Lambda when objects are created. They upload 1000 objects simultaneously. Will all 1000 Lambda invocations execute?", opts:["No — S3 events are best-effort and some may be lost","Yes — S3 event notifications are guaranteed delivery (at least once). All 1000 events will trigger Lambda invocations (subject to Lambda concurrency limits). If Lambda is throttled, S3 retries the invocation.","Only 100 concurrent invocations are allowed","S3 queues events and processes sequentially"], correct:1, exp:"S3 event notifications provide at-least-once delivery. All 1000 object creation events will trigger Lambda invocations. Lambda scales concurrently to handle them (up to 1000 concurrent executions initial burst in most regions). If Lambda's concurrency limit is hit, S3 retries with exponential backoff. Events may arrive slightly out of order or be delivered more than once (at-least-once). For guaranteed ordering and exactly-once, use S3 → SQS → Lambda (FIFO queue).", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon FSx for Lustre for their HPC workload. The file system is linked to an S3 bucket. What does this integration provide?", opts:["FSx for Lustre replaces S3 entirely","FSx for Lustre presents S3 objects as a POSIX file system — data is lazily loaded from S3 on first access (no upfront data copying). Results can be written back to S3 via hsm_archive command. Provides high-performance file system interface over S3 data.","S3 data must be fully copied to FSx before use","FSx for Lustre and S3 are unrelated services"], correct:1, exp:"FSx for Lustre + S3 integration: (1) Link FSx file system to an S3 bucket. (2) S3 objects appear as files in the Lustre file system (metadata loaded, data lazy-loaded on first read). (3) HPC applications read/write using standard POSIX file operations at hundreds of GB/s throughput. (4) Results written to FSx can be exported back to S3 (hsm_archive). This combines S3's durability/cost with Lustre's performance. No need to copy data upfront — it streams from S3 on demand.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses AWS CodeDeploy for EC2 deployments. A deployment fails on 3 out of 10 instances. CodeDeploy automatically rolls back. After investigation, they fix the issue. When they redeploy, only the 3 failed instances receive the deployment (not all 10). Why?", opts:["CodeDeploy remembers which instances failed and only targets them","This is incorrect — CodeDeploy redeploys to ALL instances in the deployment group on a new deployment. A new deployment targets all instances regardless of previous deployment state.","CodeDeploy maintains a diff of deployed versions per instance","Only failed instances are out of date"], correct:1, exp:"Each new CodeDeploy deployment targets ALL instances in the deployment group — it doesn't track or selectively deploy to 'failed' instances. If only 3 received a new deployment, check: (1) the deployment group membership (maybe 7 instances were removed), (2) deployment configuration (minimum healthy instances might cause early stop), (3) whether it's a rollback (which re-deploys the previous revision to all instances). New deployments always target the full deployment group.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon Kinesis Data Streams. They need to process records exactly once (no duplicates in the consumer). Kinesis guarantees at-least-once delivery. How can they achieve exactly-once processing?", opts:["Kinesis provides exactly-once delivery natively","Implement idempotency in the consumer — use a checkpoint/deduplication mechanism (e.g., DynamoDB table storing processed sequence numbers). Before processing a record, check if its sequence number was already processed.","Use Kinesis FIFO mode (doesn't exist)","Set the consumer to acknowledge each record (Kinesis doesn't have per-record acknowledgment like SQS)"], correct:1, exp:"Kinesis provides at-least-once delivery — consumers may see the same record during resharding, Lambda retries, or KCL checkpointing failures. For exactly-once PROCESSING: implement idempotent consumers. Pattern: (1) Read record, (2) Check DynamoDB/Redis if sequence number was processed, (3) If not: process + write sequence number atomically, (4) If yes: skip. Kinesis Enhanced Fan-Out + Lambda with bisect-on-error also helps. Exactly-once is always a consumer-side responsibility in streaming.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company wants to restrict which AMIs can be used to launch EC2 instances in their account. Only approved, hardened AMIs from their central security team should be launchable. How can they enforce this?", opts:["Security Group rules restricting by AMI (SGs don't have AMI conditions)","IAM policy with a Condition that restricts ec2:RunInstances to specific AMI IDs (Condition: StringEquals: ec2:ImageId: [ami-xxx, ami-yyy])","AWS Config rule detecting non-approved AMIs (detective, not preventive)","Remove all non-approved AMIs from the account (doesn't prevent using public AMIs)"], correct:1, exp:"IAM policy with Condition on ec2:ImageId: only allows RunInstances with specific AMI IDs. If someone tries to launch with an unapproved AMI → AccessDenied. This is PREVENTIVE control. Also: use ec2:ImageId condition with tag-based matching (ec2:ResourceTag/approved=true) for more maintainable approach as AMI list changes. SCP version works organization-wide. AWS Config can detect but not prevent. This is the IAM condition-based enforcement pattern.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon Aurora MySQL. They want to clone the production database for testing without impacting production performance and without waiting hours for the copy. What Aurora feature enables this?", opts:["Create a snapshot and restore (takes time proportional to database size)","Aurora Cloning — creates a copy of the database in MINUTES regardless of size (uses copy-on-write). The clone shares storage with the original initially, only allocating new storage for modified pages.","Create a Read Replica and promote it (takes time for replication to catch up)","Export to S3 and reimport (very slow for large databases)"], correct:1, exp:"Aurora Cloning uses copy-on-write: the clone initially shares the same underlying storage as the source (no data copy needed). Only pages that are MODIFIED diverge and allocate new storage. A 10TB database clones in ~2 minutes. No performance impact on the source. Use cases: testing with production data, running analytics without affecting production, creating development copies. Cost: only pay for storage used by modified pages. Extremely efficient for large databases.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses API Gateway HTTP API. They want to automatically validate request bodies against a JSON schema (reject requests with missing required fields before reaching the backend). Does HTTP API support this?", opts:["Yes — HTTP APIs support request validation with JSON schemas","No — Request validation with JSON Schema models is only available on REST APIs (not HTTP APIs). HTTP APIs don't have built-in request validation — validate in the backend (Lambda) instead.","Both API types support validation equally","Neither type supports request validation"], correct:1, exp:"API Gateway REST APIs support: Request Validation (body, query parameters, headers against JSON Schema models). HTTP APIs do NOT have built-in request validation — this is one of the feature trade-offs for HTTP APIs being cheaper ($1/million vs $3.50/million). With HTTP APIs: validate in the Lambda function code or use a middleware/framework layer. If request validation is critical and you want it at the gateway level, use REST API. Important feature parity distinction for the exam.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company processes images uploaded to S3. They want to generate thumbnails automatically. The system must handle 0 to 10,000 uploads per minute. Which architecture is MOST cost-effective and scalable?", opts:["EC2 Auto Scaling group polling S3 for new objects","S3 Event Notification → Lambda function (scales automatically from 0 to thousands of concurrent executions, pay only for processing time)","ECS Fargate service with auto-scaling","AWS Batch for image processing"], correct:1, exp:"S3 Event → Lambda: perfectly serverless. At 0 uploads: zero cost. At 10,000/minute: Lambda scales to thousands of concurrent executions automatically. Each invocation processes one image (download from S3, resize, upload thumbnail to S3). Pay only for compute time (~100-500ms per image). No idle infrastructure. Lambda handles the 0 to 10,000 variability without pre-provisioning. EC2/ECS require minimum running capacity even at zero load.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Backup. They want to ensure that backup copies CANNOT be deleted by anyone (including admins) before the retention period expires, for ransomware protection. What feature provides this?", opts:["Backup retention period (can be manually overridden by admins)","AWS Backup Vault Lock — once locked in compliance mode, backup recovery points CANNOT be deleted by any user (including root) before the retention period. Similar to S3 Object Lock Compliance mode.","IAM policies denying backup deletion (admins can modify their own policies)","S3 Glacier Vault Lock on the backup vault"], correct:1, exp:"AWS Backup Vault Lock (Compliance mode): makes all recovery points in the vault immutable. Once locked: backups cannot be deleted or the lock changed by anyone (including root) for the specified retention period. This protects against: ransomware (attacker can't delete backups), insider threats (malicious admin can't purge backups), and accidental deletion. Must be enabled proactively. After lock, there's a cooling period before it becomes irreversible.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses ALB with path-based routing: /api/* goes to ECS service, /static/* goes to S3 (via Lambda or another target). They want to serve static assets from S3 through the ALB. Is this possible natively?", opts:["Yes — ALB can directly target S3 buckets","No — ALB targets must be EC2, IP, Lambda, or containers. To serve S3 content through ALB: use a Lambda function target that proxies to S3. OR better: use CloudFront with S3 origin for static assets (don't route static through ALB at all).","ALB integrates with S3 via a special target group type","Use NLB instead for S3 routing"], correct:1, exp:"ALB target types: Instance, IP, Lambda function, or Application (new). S3 is NOT a valid ALB target. Options: (1) Lambda target group: Lambda retrieves object from S3 and returns it (adds latency and cost). (2) Better architecture: serve /static/* from CloudFront + S3 directly (not through ALB). Only route /api/* through ALB. Use different DNS records or CloudFront behaviors to split static vs API traffic. The 'serve everything through one ALB' approach isn't optimal for static content.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses DynamoDB with an Auto Scaling policy. They see throttling at the START of traffic spikes even though auto-scaling is configured. By the time scaling takes effect (2-3 minutes), the spike has already caused errors. How can they handle sudden spikes better?", opts:["Switch to on-demand capacity (handles spikes up to 2x previous peak instantly)","Use DynamoDB reserved capacity for the spike level","Pre-warm the table by sending dummy traffic before anticipated spikes","Both A (on-demand for unpredictable spikes) and C (scheduled scaling for predictable spikes) are valid approaches depending on spike predictability"], correct:3, exp:"Auto-scaling reacts to CloudWatch alarms with a 1-5 minute delay — too slow for sudden spikes. Solutions: (1) On-demand mode: instantly handles up to 2x the previous traffic peak. Good for unpredictable spikes. (2) Scheduled scaling (Application Auto Scaling scheduled actions): pre-scale capacity BEFORE predictable spikes (e.g., scale up 5 minutes before peak hours). (3) Provisioned with higher base capacity. Choose based on predictability of traffic patterns. On-demand for unpredictable, scheduled for predictable.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company needs their Lambda function to access resources in TWO different VPCs (VPC-A and VPC-B). Lambda can only be attached to ONE VPC. How can they solve this?", opts:["Attach Lambda to both VPCs (not possible — Lambda supports only one VPC configuration)","Attach Lambda to VPC-A, peer VPC-A with VPC-B (VPC Peering or Transit Gateway). Lambda accesses VPC-B resources through the peering connection.","Create two Lambda functions — one per VPC","Use PrivateLink between the VPCs"], correct:1, exp:"Lambda can be associated with ONE VPC (one set of subnets). To reach resources in multiple VPCs: connect the VPCs using VPC Peering or Transit Gateway. Lambda in VPC-A can route to VPC-B via the peering connection. Requirements: non-overlapping CIDRs, peering connection/TGW in place, route table entries in Lambda's subnet pointing VPC-B CIDR to the peering/TGW. This is standard VPC connectivity — Lambda uses the subnet's route table like any other resource.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses CodePipeline for CI/CD. The pipeline deploys to ECS Fargate. They want to run integration tests AFTER deployment and AUTOMATICALLY rollback if tests fail. Which deployment controller supports this?", opts:["ECS rolling update (no automatic rollback on test failure)","ECS with CodeDeploy Blue/Green deployment — deploys new task set (green), routes test traffic, runs validation tests, then shifts production traffic. If tests fail: automatically rolls back to the original task set (blue).","Manual testing between pipeline stages","CloudFormation deploy with rollback (doesn't run tests)"], correct:1, exp:"CodeDeploy Blue/Green for ECS: (1) Deploy new task set (green) alongside current (blue). (2) Route test traffic to green (test listener on a different port). (3) CodeDeploy lifecycle hooks run validation (Lambda function executing integration tests). (4) If tests pass: shift production traffic to green, terminate blue. (5) If tests fail OR CloudWatch alarm triggers: automatic rollback (traffic stays on blue, green terminated). This is the only fully automated deploy+test+rollback pattern for ECS.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company needs to analyze their AWS spending and identify cost optimization opportunities automatically. Which AWS service provides recommendations (right-sizing, RI purchase, idle resources)?", opts:["AWS Cost Explorer (shows costs but limited recommendations)","AWS Trusted Advisor (provides cost optimization checks: idle instances, underutilized EBS, unused EIPs, RI recommendations)","AWS Compute Optimizer (ML-based right-sizing recommendations for EC2, Lambda, ECS, EBS)","All three provide different cost optimization insights — use them together"], correct:3, exp:"Three complementary services: (1) AWS Cost Explorer: spending visualization + RI/Savings Plan purchase recommendations. (2) Trusted Advisor: operational best practices including cost (idle resources, underutilized instances, unattached EIPs/EBS). (3) Compute Optimizer: ML-based analysis recommending optimal instance types, Lambda memory, EBS volume types based on actual utilization patterns. Together they provide: spend visibility, waste identification, and right-sizing intelligence. Use all three for comprehensive cost optimization.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon SNS to send push notifications to mobile devices. They have 10 million registered devices. When they publish a message to a topic, does SNS send 10 million individual push notifications?", opts:["No — SNS topics can only have 12.5 million subscriptions but can't send to mobile directly","Yes — SNS Mobile Push sends individual push notifications to each registered device endpoint. Publishing to a topic with 10M subscribed endpoints triggers 10M platform-specific pushes (APNS for iOS, FCM for Android).","SNS broadcasts to all devices simultaneously in one call","SNS can only send SMS, not push notifications"], correct:1, exp:"SNS Mobile Push: register each device as a Platform Endpoint, subscribe endpoints to a Topic. Publishing to the topic triggers individual push notifications to each platform endpoint (Apple APNS, Google FCM, Amazon ADM, etc.). SNS handles the scale (millions of pushes), retries, and per-platform API formatting. For 10M devices: one Publish API call → 10M individual push notifications. Also supports Direct Publish to single endpoints without topics.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses EBS volumes (gp3). They want to take consistent snapshots of a database running on EC2. The database uses multiple EBS volumes (data + logs). They need ALL volumes to be snapshotted at the same point in time. What ensures consistency?", opts:["Take snapshots of each volume individually (risk of inconsistency between volumes)","Use EBS Multi-Volume Snapshots (crash-consistent snapshots of multiple volumes attached to the same instance, taken at the same point in time)","Stop the instance before snapshotting (causes downtime)","Use AWS Backup with a multi-volume policy"], correct:1, exp:"EBS Multi-Volume Snapshots: create crash-consistent snapshots of ALL EBS volumes attached to an instance in a single API call. All volumes are snapshotted at the same point-in-time — ensuring consistency across data, logs, and any other volumes. For application-consistent snapshots: freeze the filesystem (fsfreeze) or use VSS (Windows) before the multi-volume snapshot, then thaw after. AWS Backup also supports multi-volume consistency. This ensures recoverability for multi-volume databases.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon Cognito User Pools. They want to customize the authentication flow — for example, adding a CAPTCHA challenge or custom challenge (security question) after username/password. What Cognito feature enables this?", opts:["Cognito doesn't support custom authentication flows","Lambda Triggers — Cognito User Pools invoke Lambda functions at various points in the auth flow (pre-authentication, define auth challenge, create auth challenge, verify auth challenge). These allow custom authentication logic.","Custom authentication requires building your own identity provider","Cognito only supports standard username/password or social login"], correct:1, exp:"Cognito Lambda Triggers customize authentication: (1) Define Auth Challenge: decide what challenge to present (CAPTCHA, OTP, security question). (2) Create Auth Challenge: generate challenge parameters (CAPTCHA image, question text). (3) Verify Auth Challenge Response: validate the user's answer. This enables: multi-factor custom challenges, CAPTCHA, risk-based authentication, and any custom challenge-response flow. The triggers integrate into Cognito's secure authentication pipeline without building a custom IdP.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses S3 for a data lake with 100TB across 50 million objects. They need an inventory of all objects (size, storage class, encryption status, last modified) for auditing. Running ListObjects at this scale is slow and expensive. What is the recommended approach?", opts:["Use S3 List API with pagination (very slow for 50M objects, API costs)","S3 Inventory — a scheduled report (daily or weekly) that provides a complete list of objects with metadata (CSV, ORC, or Parquet) delivered to a target bucket. No API calls needed.","CloudWatch metrics for object counts","AWS Config for S3 object inventory (Config tracks buckets, not individual objects)"], correct:1, exp:"S3 Inventory: automated, scheduled object listing delivered as CSV/ORC/Parquet to a destination bucket. Includes: bucket, key, size, last modified, storage class, encryption status, replication status, and more. Available daily or weekly. For 50M objects: Inventory generates the report efficiently without millions of API calls. Query the report with Athena for analysis. Much faster, cheaper, and more reliable than ListObjectsV2 at scale. Also used as manifest for S3 Batch Operations.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company has an existing on-premises application that uses SMB file shares (Windows). They want to give the application access to S3 storage without modifying the application. Which service provides an SMB interface to S3?", opts:["FSx for Windows File Server (independent file system, not S3-backed)","AWS Storage Gateway File Gateway — presents S3 buckets as SMB (or NFS) file shares to on-premises applications. Files written via SMB are stored as S3 objects. Local cache provides low-latency access to recent files.","S3 directly supports SMB protocol (it doesn't)","AWS Transfer Family (SFTP/FTP, not SMB)"], correct:1, exp:"Storage Gateway File Gateway: deploys a VM on-premises, presents S3 buckets as SMB or NFS file shares. On-premises applications read/write files normally — Gateway stores them as S3 objects. Local disk cache keeps recently accessed files for low-latency access. Changes sync asynchronously to S3. Use cases: cloud backup via file shares, extending storage to S3, hybrid cloud file access. The application sees a normal file share — no code changes needed. No way to access S3 via SMB natively.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon Athena to query S3 data. Their queries are returning correct results but taking 5+ minutes. The table has 2TB of data in JSON format with no partitioning. Which optimization will have the GREATEST impact?", opts:["Add more Athena engines (Athena auto-scales, you can't add engines)","Convert data to Parquet format AND add partitioning — Parquet reduces scan volume (columnar), partitioning eliminates irrelevant data entirely. Together can reduce scan from 2TB to <50GB.","Use Athena prepared statements (performance same, just reuse)","Increase Athena workgroup query result size"], correct:1, exp:"Two highest-impact Athena optimizations: (1) PARQUET/ORC: columnar format means Athena reads only needed columns (if query uses 5/50 columns = 90% reduction). Also compresses 5-10x better. (2) PARTITIONING: organize data by commonly-filtered columns (date, region). Athena only scans relevant partitions. Together: 2TB JSON → ~200GB Parquet (compression + columnar) × partition pruning (e.g., query 1 day of 365 = 0.5GB scanned). From 5+ minutes to seconds, and from $10/query to $0.003.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Organizations with Service Control Policies. They want an SCP that allows ALL services EXCEPT preventing anyone from leaving the Organization (organizations:LeaveOrganization) and disabling CloudTrail. What SCP structure?", opts:["Allow all services, then deny the specific dangerous actions in the same SCP","Attach the default FullAWSAccess SCP (allows everything) PLUS a second SCP that explicitly DENIEs organizations:LeaveOrganization and cloudtrail:StopLogging/DeleteTrail. Deny always wins over Allow in SCPs.","Only use deny SCPs, never allow","Replace FullAWSAccess with a custom allow SCP listing all permitted services"], correct:1, exp:"SCP best practice for guardrails: keep FullAWSAccess attached (broad allow) + attach additional deny SCPs for specific dangerous actions. Deny always overrides Allow in IAM policy evaluation. This is simpler than maintaining an allowlist of every service. Common deny SCP actions: LeaveOrganization, StopLogging, DeleteTrail, DisableGuardDuty, remove encryption, modify critical resources. This is called the 'guardrail' pattern — permissive base + specific preventions.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon ElastiCache Redis. They need to persist cached data to survive a node restart (maintenance or failure). Which Redis feature should they enable?", opts:["Redis backup/snapshots (point-in-time, not continuous)","Redis AOF (Append-Only File) persistence — logs every write operation to disk. On restart, Redis replays the AOF to restore all data. Combined with Multi-AZ replication for HA.","Redis is in-memory only and can't persist data","Enable RDB snapshots only (data between snapshots is lost)"], correct:1, exp:"ElastiCache Redis supports two persistence mechanisms: (1) RDB snapshots: periodic point-in-time backups (lose data since last snapshot on crash). (2) AOF (Append-Only File): logs every write to disk, replayed on restart (minimal data loss — at most 1 second). For maximum durability: enable AOF + Multi-AZ (synchronous replication to standby in another AZ). If a node fails, failover to standby with zero data loss. AOF protects against process restarts, Multi-AZ against node/AZ failures.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses CloudFront with Lambda@Edge. They want to perform URL rewriting (e.g., /products/123 → /index.html?id=123) BEFORE the request reaches the origin. Which Lambda@Edge event type should they use?", opts:["Viewer Request (before CloudFront checks cache — good for auth but modifies ALL requests including cached ones)","Origin Request — triggered AFTER cache check, BEFORE sending to origin. URL rewriting here only affects cache misses (reduces Lambda invocations). Modified URL fetches the correct content from origin.","Origin Response (too late — response already generated)","Viewer Response (too late — response going to client)"], correct:1, exp:"Origin Request event: fires only on cache MISSES (when CloudFront needs to fetch from origin). URL rewriting here: (1) reduces Lambda@Edge invocations (cached requests don't trigger it), (2) modifies the request sent to origin (origin sees /index.html?id=123), (3) CloudFront caches the response against the ORIGINAL URL (/products/123). Viewer Request fires for EVERY request (more invocations, higher cost). For URL rewriting, Origin Request is more efficient unless the rewriting affects caching behavior.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon RDS for PostgreSQL. They enable Performance Insights to troubleshoot slow queries. What does Performance Insights provide that standard CloudWatch metrics don't?", opts:["CPU and memory metrics (CloudWatch already provides these)","Database-level wait event analysis — shows which SQL queries are waiting on what (I/O, locks, CPU, memory), number of active sessions, and identifies exactly which queries are causing load. Visual breakdown of database load by wait type, SQL, user, and host.","Storage metrics (CloudWatch provides FreeStorageSpace)","Connection count (CloudWatch provides DatabaseConnections)"], correct:1, exp:"Performance Insights provides DB-level visibility that CloudWatch can't: (1) Active Session History (ASH): how many sessions are running/waiting and WHY (wait events: I/O, lock, CPU, etc.). (2) Top SQL: which queries consume the most resources. (3) Load breakdown: DB load by wait event, SQL statement, user, host. This pinpoints: 'Query X is waiting on locks held by Query Y', or '80% of DB load is I/O wait from this SELECT'. CloudWatch shows infrastructure metrics; Performance Insights shows database workload analysis.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon MQ (RabbitMQ broker). They need to migrate from RabbitMQ to a fully serverless messaging solution that requires zero broker management. Which service is the closest equivalent?", opts:["Amazon SQS (queue semantics but not a message broker with routing/exchanges)","Amazon EventBridge (event routing with rules, similar to RabbitMQ exchanges/routing patterns but for events rather than messages)","Amazon SNS + SQS (pub/sub + queuing — closest pattern to RabbitMQ's exchange → queue model)","Amazon MSK Serverless (Kafka, different paradigm from RabbitMQ)"], correct:2, exp:"RabbitMQ pattern: Publishers → Exchanges (routing logic) → Queues → Consumers. AWS serverless equivalent: Publishers → SNS Topics (fan-out like exchanges) → SQS Queues → Consumers. SNS provides pub/sub routing (like exchanges), SQS provides reliable queuing (like queues). Combined: topic-based routing with per-subscriber queues. Message filtering on SNS subscriptions mimics RabbitMQ's routing keys. This eliminates broker management while maintaining the publish/subscribe/queue pattern.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Fargate. Their containers need to write temporary files during processing (scratch space). Where can Fargate tasks write temporary data?", opts:["Fargate tasks have no writable storage","Fargate provides ephemeral storage (20GB by default, configurable up to 200GB) — writable, local to the task, deleted when task stops. Also supports EFS volumes for persistent shared storage across tasks.","Must attach an EBS volume (not supported with Fargate)","Must use S3 for all file writes"], correct:1, exp:"Fargate ephemeral storage: each task gets ephemeral storage (default 20GB, configurable 21-200GB) mounted at /tmp or any path. It's local SSD — fast read/write, but deleted when the task terminates. For persistent or shared storage: mount an EFS file system (shared across tasks and persists independently). EBS volumes are NOT supported with Fargate. Ephemeral storage is for: temp files, caches, scratch space. EFS is for: shared data, persistent state, large datasets.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses CloudFormation. They accidentally deleted a resource directly in the console that was created by a stack. The stack now shows DRIFTED status. What is 'drift' and how do they fix it?", opts:["Drift means CloudFormation template has syntax errors","Drift means the actual resource state differs from what CloudFormation expects (template definition). Fix: either (1) import the resource back into the stack, (2) update the template to match current state, or (3) delete/recreate using CloudFormation to resync.","Drift can't be detected","Delete the entire stack and recreate"], correct:1, exp:"CloudFormation drift detection compares actual resource state with the template definition. Sources of drift: manual console changes, CLI modifications, or resource deletion outside CloudFormation. Resolution options: (1) Resource import: bring existing resources under stack management. (2) Update template to match reality (if the manual change was intentional). (3) Stack update to revert to template state (overwrites manual changes). For deleted resources: import a new one or let CloudFormation recreate on next update. Drift detection is a diagnostic tool, not automatic remediation.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company has a web application that uses cookies for session management. They deploy behind CloudFront. Users report being logged out randomly. What is likely happening?", opts:["CloudFront is caching responses that include Set-Cookie headers — different users get each other's cached sessions. Solution: configure CloudFront to forward cookies to origin (add cookies to cache key or use origin request policy with cookies forwarded).","The application has a session bug","DNS resolution is inconsistent","SSL certificates are expiring"], correct:0, exp:"CloudFront caches responses by default without considering cookies. If a response includes Set-Cookie, it gets cached and served to OTHER users (session leakage). Fix: (1) Add cookies to the cache key (CloudFront caches separate versions per cookie value). (2) Use Cache-Control: private on responses with Set-Cookie. (3) Forward cookies to origin via origin request policy. For APIs with session cookies: always forward relevant cookies. For static assets: don't forward cookies (cache efficiently). This is a critical CloudFront + sessions misconfiguration.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses Step Functions for an order processing workflow. One step requires human approval (a manager must approve orders over $10,000). How do they implement a human-in-the-loop step?", opts:["Step Functions can't pause for human input","Use a Task state with .waitForTaskToken — Step Functions pauses execution, sends a task token to an SNS/SQS/API endpoint. The manager receives the token (via email/Slack). When they approve: a Lambda/API call sends SendTaskSuccess with the token, resuming the workflow.","Use a Wait state for a fixed duration","Send an email and poll for response"], correct:1, exp:"Task .waitForTaskToken pattern for human approval: (1) Step Functions enters the Task state and generates a unique token. (2) Token is sent to the approval system (email via SES with approve/reject links, Slack message with buttons, or a web UI). (3) Execution PAUSES (no charges while waiting). (4) When manager clicks 'Approve': backend calls SendTaskSuccess(token, output). (5) Step Functions resumes with the output. Can wait up to 1 year. Heartbeat timeout optional for escalation.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon CloudWatch Container Insights for their EKS cluster. What additional visibility does Container Insights provide beyond standard CloudWatch metrics?", opts:["Only standard EC2 metrics (CPU, memory at instance level)","Container-level metrics: CPU/memory/network per pod, per container, per service, per namespace. Also captures cluster-level metrics, task-level metrics, and integrates with CloudWatch Logs for container stdout/stderr. Provides a pre-built dashboard for Kubernetes observability.","Only Kubernetes API server metrics","Container Insights only works with ECS, not EKS"], correct:1, exp:"Container Insights for EKS provides Kubernetes-native metrics that CloudWatch can't capture alone: per-pod CPU/memory/network, per-namespace resource usage, cluster utilization, node-level metrics with Kubernetes context (which pods on which nodes), and performance logs. Pre-built dashboards show: cluster → namespace → service → pod → container drill-down. Integrates with CloudWatch Logs Insights for log analysis. Requires CloudWatch agent (or Fluent Bit) DaemonSet deployment.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses RDS SQL Server. They reach the maximum storage limit (16TB for SQL Server on RDS). The database needs more storage. What are their options?", opts:["RDS storage can be expanded beyond 16TB for SQL Server (it cannot — 16TB is the max for SQL Server engine)","Migrate to Aurora (Aurora doesn't support SQL Server engine). Options: (1) Shard the database across multiple RDS SQL Server instances, (2) Archive old data to S3/Glacier, (3) Migrate to a different engine that supports more storage.","Use EBS volumes directly (RDS manages its own storage)","Enable storage auto-scaling beyond the limit (auto-scaling respects the 16TB max)"], correct:1, exp:"RDS SQL Server has a 16TB storage limit (engine limitation). When reached, options: (1) Archive historical data to S3 (reduce active database size), (2) Partition/shard across multiple RDS SQL Server instances (complex), (3) Migrate to Aurora PostgreSQL or MySQL (support up to 128TB, but requires application code changes for SQL Server-specific features). (4) Self-manage SQL Server on EC2 with larger storage (lose managed benefits). Aurora doesn't have a SQL Server-compatible engine.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Glue for ETL. Their source data has sensitive fields (credit card numbers). They need to detect and mask these fields during ETL processing. Which Glue feature helps?", opts:["Glue can't detect sensitive data","AWS Glue Sensitive Data Detection — automatically identifies PII patterns (credit cards, SSN, emails) in data during ETL. Use the detect() transform to find sensitive columns, then apply masking/redaction/hashing/encryption transforms before writing to the target.","Use Amazon Macie instead (Macie scans S3, not in ETL pipelines)","Manual regex matching in the ETL script"], correct:1, exp:"AWS Glue has built-in sensitive data detection: identifies PII using predefined patterns (credit cards, SSN, phone numbers, emails, etc.) and custom patterns (regex). In your Glue ETL job: (1) detect() identifies which columns contain sensitive data, (2) Apply transforms: mask (replace with ***), hash (SHA-256), encrypt (KMS), redact (remove), or tokenize. This integrates data protection directly into the ETL pipeline — sensitive data never reaches the target unprotected.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company wants to use AWS for disaster recovery of their on-premises VMware environment. They want continuous replication with RPO of minutes and the ability to launch recovery instances quickly. Which service?", opts:["AWS Backup (doesn't replicate on-premises VMware)","AWS Elastic Disaster Recovery (DRS) — continuous block-level replication from on-premises to AWS, RPO in seconds/minutes, launch recovery instances in minutes during disaster, automated failback when primary site recovers","AWS Migration Hub","VM Import/Export (one-time, not continuous)"], correct:1, exp:"AWS Elastic Disaster Recovery (formerly CloudEndure DR): installs a lightweight agent on source servers (physical, virtual, cloud). Continuously replicates block-level data to AWS (RPO: seconds). During disaster: launch fully-provisioned EC2 instances in minutes (RTO: minutes). After primary site recovers: automated failback replication. Supports: VMware, Hyper-V, physical servers, other clouds. Purpose-built for DR — not migration (though related technology). Replaces the need for secondary data center DR.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses CloudWatch Synthetics (Canaries) to monitor their API. What do Canaries provide that regular CloudWatch Alarms on application metrics don't?", opts:["Faster metric collection","Canaries PROACTIVELY test endpoints by running scripted checks (like a synthetic user) on a schedule — they detect problems BEFORE real users are affected. They test from outside the application (external perspective), verify multi-step workflows, and catch issues that internal metrics miss (DNS failures, certificate expiry, third-party dependency failures).","Higher resolution metrics","Support for custom metrics"], correct:1, exp:"CloudWatch Synthetics Canaries: scheduled scripts (Node.js/Python) that simulate user behavior externally. They: (1) Hit endpoints on a schedule (every 1-5 minutes), (2) Verify response status, content, latency, (3) Capture screenshots (for visual monitoring), (4) Test multi-step flows (login → navigate → checkout). KEY DIFFERENCE from application metrics: Canaries detect issues from the USER'S perspective including problems outside your application (DNS, CDN, external dependencies, network paths). They find issues before real users report them.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses S3 versioning. They want to permanently delete a specific version of an object. How is this done?", opts:["Delete the object normally (this only adds a delete marker, doesn't remove versions)","Specify the Version ID in the DELETE request — s3:DeleteObject with versionId parameter permanently removes that specific version. Without versionId, a delete marker is added but no data is removed.","Versions can never be permanently deleted","Disable versioning first then delete"], correct:1, exp:"With versioning enabled: DELETE without versionId → adds delete marker (soft delete, object hidden but all versions preserved). DELETE with versionId → permanently removes that specific version (hard delete, unrecoverable). To fully delete all versions of an object: delete each version individually by versionId + delete all delete markers. S3 Lifecycle rules can automate this: expire noncurrent versions after N days. MFA Delete can protect against accidental permanent deletion of versions.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company runs Apache Spark jobs on Amazon EMR for data processing. They want to improve job performance by caching intermediate data between Spark stages. EMR provides enhanced caching. What is it?", opts:["Standard Spark in-memory caching (RDD.cache())","EMR Runtime for Apache Spark includes optimized caching and EMRFS S3-optimized committer. EMR also supports instance store (local NVMe SSDs) for Spark shuffle and cache data — much faster than EBS for intermediate data.","Redis caching for Spark results","DynamoDB as Spark cache"], correct:1, exp:"EMR optimizations for Spark: (1) EMR Runtime: optimized Spark execution with performance improvements over open-source Spark. (2) Instance store NVMe SSDs: use i3/d2/r5d instances for Spark shuffle/cache — local SSD is faster than EBS for ephemeral intermediate data. (3) EMRFS S3 optimized committer: faster S3 writes avoiding rename operations. (4) Dynamic allocation: adjusts executor count based on workload. These EMR-specific optimizations improve Spark performance 2-3x over vanilla Spark.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses AWS PrivateLink to expose their service to customers in other AWS accounts. What does PrivateLink provide that VPC Peering doesn't?", opts:["PrivateLink is slower than VPC Peering","PrivateLink exposes a SPECIFIC service (via NLB endpoint) without exposing the entire VPC network. Consumer accesses the service via an interface VPC endpoint in their own VPC. No route table changes, no CIDR overlap concerns, no broad network access — only the specific service port is accessible.","They provide the same functionality","PrivateLink requires Direct Connect"], correct:1, exp:"PrivateLink vs VPC Peering: VPC Peering connects TWO ENTIRE VPCs (all resources can potentially communicate, must manage route tables, CIDRs can't overlap). PrivateLink exposes ONE SERVICE: provider puts an NLB in front of their service → creates a VPC endpoint service → consumers create interface endpoints in their VPCs. Only the service is accessible — no other network exposure. CIDRs can overlap. Scales to thousands of consumers. This is the model for SaaS/shared services.", domain:1},
]
